ouse, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Woolley, Yorkshire, England":"Woolley, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Wollay","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Shropshire and Lancashire): variant of the Devon surname <b>Woolland</b>, perhaps a habitational name from Woolland in Dorset, named from Old English <i>wynne</i> ‘pasture, meadow’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’. Alternatively, but less likely, a topographic name from Middle English <i>wough</i> ‘bent, crooked’ + <i>land(e)</i>, <i>lond(e)</i> ‘land’ (Old English <i>wōh</i> + <i>land</i>), perhaps denoting a person who lived at or near a bend in a stream or river, or for someone from any place so named, such as Wollensbrook in Great Amwell (Hertfordshire). This surname is rare in Britain.","Americanized form of German   Ulm  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wollan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerhard.","English (Staffordshire and Somerset): variant of   Wollam  .","Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farmsteads, mainly in Trøndelag, named <i>Vollan</i>, from the definite plural form of   Voll   (‘meadow’). Compare   Wollen  ."]},{"name":"Woolam","meanings":["English: variant of   Wollam  .","Americanized form of German   Ulm  ."]},{"name":"Ulm","meanings":["German:","habitational name from the city of this name in Baden-Württemberg. The placename is from the root <i>uel</i>, an unattested word meaning ‘turn, wind, roll’, or from <i>el-</i> or <i>ol-</i> ‘flow’, a reference in either case to the influx of the Blan river into the Danube.","from a short form of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Odolmar</i> (see   Ulmer   2). Compare   Ollom  ,   Ullom  ,   Ullum  ,   Wollam  , and   Woolam  ."]},{"name":"Woolen","meanings":["English: variant of   Wollam  . In northern England, the surname is unexplained."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":4,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":39,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":70,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1}